"""
MKT Context Commentary — Matthew chapters 9–10
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/matthew.json (adds ch9-10)

Historical/cultural/geographical context focus only.
NOT Greek lexical analysis (mkt-original) and NOT typology/Christology (mkt-christ).

Key context decisions for this range:
- Ch9 paralytic: four-man carry through Palestinian flat-roof house (Mark\xe2\x80\x99s version specifies roof-digging)
- Tax collectors (9:9-10): toll-farmers in Roman client-kingdom economy, social stigma
- Fasting debates (9:14-17): Pharisaic fasting practices beyond Yom Kippur
- New wine/old wineskins (9:17): Palestinian winemaking process and storage
- Jairus/bleeding woman (9:18-26): synagogue ruler\xe2\x80\x99s social position; 12-year hemorrhage and Levitical impurity
- Harvest saying (9:37-38): agricultural metaphor in harvest-dependent economy
- Ch10 mission discourse: itinerant teacher customs, hospitality networks, synagogue discipline
- "Do not go to Gentiles or Samaritans" (10:5-6): mission scope limited to Israel in first sending
- Shaking dust from feet (10:14): Jewish custom on entering/leaving Gentile territory
- Sparrows (10:29): assaria coin value; subsistence economics
- v9:11 and 10:1 already covered; merge_comm will skip those
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: Historical/cultural/geographical context for Matthew 9-10; covers more
#   Galilean healing narratives and the Mission Discourse. No Greek lexical focus.
# CHANGE? If verse keys change in data/interlinear/matthew.json, update dict keys here.
# VERIFY: Run script; confirm ch9 = 38 verses, ch10 = 42 verses in output.

MATTHEW = {
  "9": {
    "1": '<p>The "his own city" (<em>tēn idian polin</em>) is Capernaum (4:13), Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 adopted base on the northwestern shore of the Sea of Galilee. Capernaum was a prosperous fishing and trade town at the intersection of the Via Maris trade route, with a significant population, synagogue, and likely a Roman customs post. The return by boat from the Gadarene territory (8:28-34) completes the first of several cross-lake journeys in Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s narrative.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The paralytic\xe2\x80\x99s friends brought him on a mat (<em>krabatton</em> in Mark; <em>klinēn</em> in Matthew = a stretcher/bed). In Palestinian village houses of the first century, roofs were typically flat, constructed of timber beams covered with mud plaster, brushwood, and packed earth — Mark 2:4 describes digging through the roof to lower the man. This was an act of costly, determined persistence: damaging a roof required repair and created an obligation to the homeowner. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 address — "take heart, child (<em>teknon</em>)" — is warmly familial before the healing declaration.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The scribes\xe2\x80\x99 charge of blasphemy (<em>blasphēmei</em>) follows logically from Jewish monotheistic theology: the forgiveness of sins was reserved for God alone. Isa 43:25 and 44:22 explicitly present YHWH as the one who blots out transgressions; Ps 103:3 identifies God as the one who forgives all iniquities. A human claiming to forgive sins (not just personal offenses but sin against God) was making a divine prerogative claim — hence blasphemy. The scribes\xe2\x80\x99 reasoning is theologically sound; their error is in not recognizing who Jesus is.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 perception of their thoughts (<em>eidōs tas enthymēseis autōn</em>) reflects the Jewish tradition of divine heart-knowledge (1 Sam 16:7; Ps 139:1-4; Jer 17:10) now attributed to Jesus — another implicit claim. The rhetorical question "why do you think evil in your hearts?" invites self-examination rather than public confrontation, a characteristically Wisdom-style approach to opposition.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The two-step rhetorical logic — which is easier, to say "your sins are forgiven" or to say "rise and walk"? — exploits the verifiability difference. The forgiveness declaration is unverifiable by external observers; the healing command has immediate visible outcome. The argument is not that healing is harder than forgiveness, but that healing provides visible confirmation of the authority claimed in both cases. The healings function throughout Matthew as enacted arguments about Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 identity.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"That you may know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins" — the healing serves as public, verifiable evidence for the forgiveness claim. "On earth" (<em>epi tēs gēs</em>) may emphasize the surprising location of this authority: forgiveness was expected in the heavenly or eschatological realm; Jesus is exercising it in present, mundane Galilean life. The title "Son of Man" here draws on Dan 7:13-14 where the figure receives authority and judgment from the Ancient of Days.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The healed man\xe2\x80\x99s immediate compliance — arising, taking his mat, and going to his house — was publicly visible to the crowd. In the social economy of honor and shame, a visible miracle publicly performed required a public response. The crowd\xe2\x80\x99s glorification of God (<em>edoxasan ton theon</em>) is the appropriate communal response to divine action and represents the social closure of the episode.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The crowd\xe2\x80\x99s fear and glorification of God (<em>ephobethesan kai edoxasan ton theon ton donta exousian toiautēn tois anthrōpois</em>) frames the miracle as a divine gift of authority "to men" — a notably inclusive formulation. The people\xe2\x80\x99s astonishment reflects the Jewish expectation of eschatological restoration: the coming age would bring healing and forgiveness; the crowd witnesses these happening in the present.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The toll-collector (<em>telōnēs</em>) named Matthew was stationed at a tax booth (<em>telōnion</em>) on the road through Capernaum, likely collecting duties on goods passing along the Via Maris or on fish exported from the region. Toll-farmers in the Roman client-kingdom economy bid for the right to collect taxes in a given district, paying Rome or Herod in advance and recouping their investment (plus profit) from travelers and traders. The system created enormous incentives for extortion and over-collection, making toll-collectors synonymous with dishonesty and collaboration with Rome in popular perception.</p><p>The call "follow me" to a toll-collector and his immediate compliance was socially scandalous: respectable teachers did not recruit from this social category. That Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s name is attached to this Gospel suggests a community that preserved and honored his memory — possibly including his administrative skills in recording Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 teaching.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The dinner at Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s house (<em>en tē̄ oikia̧</em>) was a significant public occasion: in Mediterranean culture, table fellowship was a primary social bond that expressed equality, friendship, and mutual obligation among participants. Eating with "many tax collectors and sinners" (<em>telōnai kai hamartōloi</em>) — a semi-technical designation for those outside the Pharisaic purity network — was a deliberate social statement. To share a meal was to share honor; Pharisees who observed table purity avoided this community as a contamination risk.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 response "the healthy have no need of a physician, but the sick do" employs a medical analogy widely used in Hellenistic philosophy (Diogenes Laertius; Epictetus; Seneca) to argue that philosophical teachers serve those who recognize their moral sickness. The analogy frames the dinner not as moral compromise but as therapeutic outreach: the physician\xe2\x80\x99s presence among the sick is the proper location of healing activity.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The citation of Hos 6:6 — "I desire mercy and not sacrifice" — is cited twice by Matthew (here and 12:7). In its original context, Hosea was indicting Israel\xe2\x80\x99s substitution of cultic performance for the covenantal character of <em>hesed</em> (faithful loving-kindness). The prophetic critique of empty ritual without ethical transformation was a recurring theme; Jesus activates it to reframe the table-fellowship controversy. The "not... but" form is a Hebrew idiom of emphasis (preference, not absolute exclusion): mercy is prioritized over sacrifice, not sacrifice abolished.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Pharisaic fasting practices extended well beyond the single Yom Kippur fast required by Torah. By the first century, some Pharisaic groups fasted twice weekly (Monday and Thursday — cf. Lk 18:12; Didache 8:1), corresponding to the traditional days Moses ascended and descended Sinai. John the Baptist\xe2\x80\x99s disciples\xe2\x80\x99 question likely reflects their own community\xe2\x80\x99s penitential fasting practice rooted in eschatological urgency. The question is genuine: if both John\xe2\x80\x99s disciples and the Pharisees fast as signs of their religious seriousness, why don\xe2\x80\x99t Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 disciples?</p>',
    "15": '<p>The bridegroom metaphor activates Jewish eschatological wedding imagery: the coming of the Messiah was described as a wedding feast (Isa 25:6; 62:4-5; Rev 19:7-9). Fasting was inappropriate during a wedding in Jewish tradition; the festive days of a wedding week prohibited mourning practices. By describing himself as the bridegroom, Jesus frames the present season as the wedding banquet arrival — to fast would be to mourn when the bridegroom is present. The hint of removal ("when the bridegroom is taken away") anticipates the Passion.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The unshrunk cloth patch (<em>rhakos agnaphon</em> = unfulled cloth) parable addresses the incompatibility of old and new garment materials. In Palestinian textile practice, new woven cloth required fulling (washing, beating, shrinking) before being cut. Patching old (already-shrunk) cloth with new (unfulled) cloth would result in the patch shrinking after washing and tearing the surrounding garment. The analogy argues that Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 kingdom teaching cannot be simply patched onto existing religious forms — the new will destroy the old container if forced together.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Palestinian winemaking used either new clay jars or new goatskin containers (<em>askoi</em>) for fermenting wine. New wine still undergoing active fermentation released carbon dioxide; old wineskins that had already been stretched to capacity by previous fermentation had lost elasticity and would burst under new expansion pressure. New skins retained enough flexibility to accommodate the wine\xe2\x80\x99s expansion. The parable argues that the new wine of the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s arrival requires the new containers of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 community and practice, not the old institutional forms.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Jairus is identified in Mark and Luke as a <em>archōn tēs synagōgēs</em> (synagogue ruler) — a lay administrator responsible for the building, ordering of worship, and choice of readers/speakers in a local synagogue. This was a position of social standing and community leadership. His prostration before Jesus (<em>prosekynei autō̄</em>) was a remarkable act of humility from a community official, driven by desperation at his daughter\xe2\x80\x99s critical condition. The "just now died" (<em>arti eteleutēsen</em>) in Matthew contrasts with Mark/Luke where the daughter is still alive when Jairus approaches — Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s compressed account presents the situation as already hopeless from the outset.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 immediate response — "rising he followed him" — and the crowd following them creates the scene for the interruption by the hemorrhaging woman. The movement through a crowd in a village street was pressing and physical; first-century Palestinian villages were densely built with narrow paths between houses.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The woman with the twelve-year hemorrhage lived in a state of continuous Levitical impurity (Lev 15:25-30): any discharge of blood rendered a woman impure, and everything she touched or sat on became impure, and anyone touching her became impure until evening. Twelve years of this condition meant twelve years of social, religious, and relational exclusion — barred from Temple, synagogue community activities, and normal physical contact. She had spent her savings on physicians (Mark 5:26); her approach from behind to touch the fringe of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 garment was a desperate attempt at healing while minimizing her imposition.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Her internal reasoning — "if I only touch his garment, I will be healed" (<em>sōthēsomai</em> = will be saved/healed) — reflects the popular belief that holy persons\xe2\x80\x99 clothing carried healing power. The fringe (<em>kraspedon</em>, likely the <em>tzitzit</em>/tassel required by Num 15:38-40; Deut 22:12) was the garment\xe2\x80\x99s ritually significant element. Malachi 4:2 (LXX: Mal 3:20) promised that the "sun of righteousness will rise with healing in its wings (<em>kraphsin</em>)" — the word could also mean "fringes/hems," creating a messianic expectation that may underlie her specific action.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 turning, seeing her, and addressing her publicly — "take heart, daughter, your faith has saved you" — was a social act of public restoration as significant as the physical healing. By calling attention to her and acknowledging her healing publicly, Jesus reintegrated her into visible community. The declaration "your faith has saved you" attributes agency to her trust rather than to the magical contact with the garment, reframing popular healing-power beliefs within a covenantal framework of personal faith-response.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The flute players (<em>aulētas</em>) and crowd making noise (<em>thorybouménon</em>) at Jairus\xe2\x80\x99s house were professional mourners — a social institution throughout the ancient Mediterranean world. Jewish mourning required demonstrative grief: tearing garments, disheveling hair, wailing, beating the breast. Mourning professionals were hired to supplement family grief, ensuring adequate public mourning expression. The presence of a crowd already making noise suggests the girl had died very recently, as mourning began immediately upon death.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 statement "the girl has not died but is sleeping" (<em>ou gar apethanen to korasion alla katheudei</em>) provoked laughter from the professional mourners — they had verified the death. The statement\xe2\x80\x99s meaning is debated: was it a statement about the nature of her condition (coma), or a prophetic declaration about what her condition was about to become (as death is about to be reversed by resurrection)? The NT consistently uses "sleep" as a metaphor for death (1 Thess 4:13-15; John 11:11-14), suggesting Jesus is characterizing her condition from the resurrection perspective.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The expulsion of the crowd before the resurrection — putting them outside (<em>exeblēthē ho ochlos</em>) — reflects Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 consistent practice of limiting public access to his most intimate miracles (cf. Mark 5:40 where only the parents and three disciples enter). This is not secrecy for its own sake but appropriate management of the potentially overwhelming social consequences of a public resurrection demonstration. The privacy also protects the family from the mob dynamics that might follow.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The fame spreading through the district (<em>hē phēmē autē eis holēn tēn gēn ekeinēn</em>) reflects the oral communication culture of first-century Galilee. News in village networks traveled person-to-person through kinship and trading networks. A reported resurrection of a synagogue ruler\xe2\x80\x99s daughter would have spread rapidly through the tightly knit communities of the Galilee region. Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s note acknowledges this without elaborating on its social consequences.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The two blind men following Jesus with the cry "have mercy on us, Son of David" represents the first use of the Davidic messianic title in Matthew by supplicants (it appeared at 1:1 in the genealogy). The connection between the Davidic messiah and healing of the blind draws on Isa 29:18; 35:5 ("then the eyes of the blind shall be opened") and 42:7 as descriptions of the messianic age. Blind beggars in the street were a recognizable social category in antiquity; their persistent following of Jesus through streets was a public demonstration.</p>',
    "28": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 question — "do you believe that I am able to do this?" — before healing reflects a pattern of faith-engagement throughout the healing narratives. The house setting (Jesus entered the house) provides privacy for this exchange, contrasting with the public street following. The faith-question is not a test of worthiness but an activation of the covenantal relationship: healing flows through the channel of trust.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The touching of eyes (<em>hēpsato tōn ophthalmōn autōn</em>) — physical contact with the affected organ — was a recognizable ancient healing gesture. Medical practitioners and healers in the Hellenistic world used touch as part of treatment; Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 touch combined the physical gesture with the verbal declaration "according to your faith let it be to you." The formula links the healing\xe2\x80\x99s outcome explicitly to the men\xe2\x80\x99s trust.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The charge to tell no one (<em>horate mēdeis ginōsketō</em>) — the Messianic secret motif — is pragmatically motivated in Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s context: each healing that became publicly known increased the crowd pressure and political attention that threatened to derail Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 mission timing. Herod Antipas\xe2\x80\x99s earlier execution of John the Baptist demonstrated the political dangers of popular Messianic movements; Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 careful management of publicity was not false modesty but strategic.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Their spreading the news throughout the district (<em>diephēmisan auton en holē̄ tē̄ gē̄ ekeinē̄</em>) despite the charge of silence demonstrates the social impossibility of suppressing news of spectacular healing in village culture. The two healed men had strong social obligations to announce what had happened — the healing affected their whole network of family and community relationships. Cultural norms of reciprocal gratitude and public testimony overrode Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 instruction.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The mute demoniac (<em>daimonidzomenos kōphos</em>) presented Jesus with a different social challenge: the inability to speak prevented the normal communication of faith and request. In ancient medicine, mutism was commonly attributed to demonic obstruction of speech; the exorcism-healing connection (removing the demon restores speech) reflects the integrated body-spirit understanding of illness in the ancient world.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The crowds\xe2\x80\x99 response — "never was anything like this seen in Israel" (<em>oudepote ephanē houtōs en tō̄ Israēl</em>) — represents the accumulation of a series of unprecedented healings reaching a climax. The Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 counter-interpretation — "by the ruler of demons he casts out demons" — is the adversarial explanation that will be developed in 12:24. The two responses (crowd astonishment vs. Pharisaic attribution to Beelzebul) represent the divided reception of Jesus that characterizes Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s narrative.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 attribution of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 exorcisms to demonic power (<em>en tō̄ archonti tōn daimoniōn ekballei ta daimonia</em>) would become the formal charge elaborated in 12:24-32. The social function of this charge was to inoculate the population against following Jesus: if his power came from the ruler of demons rather than from God, his healings were demonic deception rather than divine intervention. This was the only available counter-explanation for undeniable exorcisms that did not attribute them to divine authorization.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The summary of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 Galilean ministry circuit — "teaching in their synagogues, proclaiming the gospel of the kingdom, healing every disease and every affliction" — mirrors the summary of 4:23, creating a structural frame around the Galilean ministry section. Synagogues (<em>synagōgai</em>) in first-century Galilee were community centers for Torah reading, teaching, prayer, and communal assembly; they were the primary public institution of village Jewish life, distinct from the Jerusalem Temple.</p>',
    "36": '<p>The compassion for the crowds (<em>esplagchnisthē peri autōn</em>) because they were "harassed and helpless, like sheep without a shepherd" (<em>hōs probata mē echonta poimena</em>) echoes the classic OT image of Israel under failed leadership (Num 27:17; 1 Kgs 22:17; Ezek 34:5-6; Zech 10:2). The political-religious context of first-century Galilee — competing factions, Roman occupation, economic stress, religious fragmentation — produced exactly the "shepherdless" condition the prophets described. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 compassion is not sentiment but a prophetically grounded recognition of leadership failure.</p>',
    "37": '<p>The harvest metaphor (<em>ho men therismos polys</em> = the harvest is great) draws on the economic reality of Galilean agriculture: the grain and olive harvests required intensive labor over a short seasonal window, and inadequate workforce meant crops left unharvested and lost. The metaphor activates an urgency that the original audience would have felt viscerally — missed harvest windows had real economic consequences. The \xe2\x80\x9cworkers\xe2\x80\x9d (<em>ergatai</em>) are those needed for the urgent eschatological gathering of people into the kingdom.</p>',
    "38": '<p>The instruction to "ask the Lord of the harvest" (<em>ton kyrion tou therismou</em>) to send workers places the initiative for mission in prayer rather than in human strategy. The Lord of the harvest is God; the mission is God\xe2\x80\x99s project, not a human organization. The prayer-request is immediately answered by Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 commissioning of the Twelve (10:1), making the pray-for-workers command and the mission commissioning two sides of the same eschatological action.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "2": '<p>The list of the Twelve Apostles places Simon Peter first and Judas Iscariot last — a deliberate framing that positions the primacy of Peter\xe2\x80\x99s confession (16:16) against the betrayal of Judas. The pairs in which the disciples are listed (Simon and Andrew; James and John; Philip and Bartholomew; etc.) may reflect their original mission partnerships (Jesus sends them "two by two" in Mark 6:7). The title "apostle" (<em>apostolos</em> = one sent out, commissioned envoy) was used in Greek for official diplomatic messengers; in Jewish usage, the <em>shaliach</em> (sent one) carried the authority of the sender.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The diversity of the Twelve\xe2\x80\x99s backgrounds is significant: fishermen (Peter, Andrew, James, John), a tax collector (Matthew), and a Zealot (Simon the Zealot, 10:4) — the last two representing opposite ends of the spectrum regarding Roman collaboration. Zealots advocated violent resistance to Roman occupation; toll collectors worked within the Roman economic system. Their co-presence in the group is historically remarkable and demonstrates that Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 community transcended the factional divisions of Galilean Jewish society.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Judas Iscariot\xe2\x80\x99s identification as "the one who betrayed him" (<em>ho kai paradous auton</em>) at his first mention in the Gospel attaches his fate to his introduction — a proleptic biographical label. The meaning of "Iscariot" is disputed: most commonly taken as <em>ish-Kerioth</em> (man of Kerioth, a town in Judah), which would make him the only non-Galilean among the Twelve. Other proposals include a connection to the Sicarii (dagger-men, an assassin group), though this etymology is chronologically problematic.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The geographical and ethnic scope of the first mission — "do not go in the way of the Gentiles and do not enter a city of Samaritans; go rather to the lost sheep of the house of Israel" — reflects the staged mission theology of Matthew: Israel first, then the nations (28:19). The restriction is temporary and strategic: Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 primary mission was the covenant community\xe2\x80\x99s restoration. Samaritans occupied a disputed middle position in Jewish ethnic taxonomy — descendants of intermarried northern Israelites and foreign settlers after the Assyrian conquest, their status as insiders or outsiders was contested.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The "lost sheep of the house of Israel" (<em>ta probata ta apolōlota oikou Israēl</em>) echoes Ezek 34\xe2\x80\x99s shepherd-failure theology and Jer 50:6\xe2\x80\x99s image of scattered sheep. The phrase frames the mission not as recruitment into a new religion but as the eschatological restoration of Israel\xe2\x80\x99s covenant people — gathering those who have been scattered through leadership failure and social marginalization.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The proclamation content — "the kingdom of heaven has come near" (<em>hēngiken hē basileia tōn ouranōn</em>) — is identical to both John the Baptist\xe2\x80\x99s proclamation (3:2) and Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 own proclamation (4:17), connecting the messengers\xe2\x80\x99 message seamlessly to the source. The disciples are not offering a new religious system but announcing an eschatological event: the reign of God is becoming present and must be responded to.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The fourfold commission — heal the sick, raise the dead, cleanse lepers, cast out demons — extends the activities of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 own ministry chapters 8-9 to the Twelve. This establishes the mission as a continuation and extension of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 own messianic activities, not merely his teaching. The principle "freely you received, freely give" (<em>dōrean elabete, dōrean dote</em>) addresses a real temptation in the ancient world: charging fees for miraculous healing was common among traveling teachers and wonder-workers, and the principle explicitly rules out the commercialization of kingdom ministry.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The mission instructions about equipment — no gold, silver, or copper coins in belts, no bag, no extra tunic, no sandals, no staff (in Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s version) — reflect the actual material conditions of itinerant teachers in the ancient world. Traveling philosophers (Cynics, Pythagoreans) and Jewish teachers operated in visible poverty as a statement of their vocation. The belt (<em>zōnē</em>) was used to carry money in a pouch attached to it; the elimination of monetary provisions signals dependence on hospitality networks rather than commercial self-sufficiency.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The principle "the worker deserves his food" (<em>axios gar ho ergatēs tēs trophēs autou</em>) — cited by Paul in 1 Tim 5:18 — establishes the basis for mission hospitality: communities that benefit from the proclamation owe support to the proclaimers. This reciprocal obligation was embedded in the ancient patron-client hospitality system; the disciples were to enter it as clients of households and communities, dependent on their hosts\xe2\x80\x99 patronage. This made the mission socially transparent: the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 dependence was a structural feature, not a failure of planning.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The instruction to inquire about a "worthy" (<em>axios</em>) host in each town reflects the practical need to identify households that would provide stable hospitality for the duration of the mission in that area. In village culture, certain households were known for hospitality; the inquiry system tapped into existing social knowledge. The instruction to stay in one house rather than moving around avoided the appearance of exploiting multiple hosts or social-climbing toward more prestigious households.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The greeting of a household with "peace" (<em>eirēnē</em>) upon entry activates the covenantal Hebrew <em>shalom</em> — comprehensive well-being and God\xe2\x80\x99s blessing. The greeting was not merely a social convention but a prophetic declaration that either took hold in the household (if worthy) or returned to the sender (if unworthy). This reflects the ancient understanding that spoken blessings and curses had effective power, returning if they found no receptive host.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The peace returning to the sender if the house is unworthy reflects Jewish wisdom about the reflexive nature of blessing and curse: if hospitality is refused and the community does not receive the message, the peace offered cannot rest there. This is not vengeful withdrawal but a description of covenantal dynamics: the blessing of the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s announcement either finds a home or does not, and the messenger is not diminished by the rejection.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Shaking the dust from the feet (<em>ektinaxate ton koniorton tōn podōn hymōn</em>) upon leaving an unreceptive house or town was a Jewish practice used when leaving Gentile territory to avoid bringing Gentile impurity into Israel. Applied here to Jewish towns that reject the kingdom proclamation, the gesture reverses the boundary: the rejecting Jewish community is being treated as outside the covenant, with the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 departure marking the boundary of responsiveness. The gesture was visible, understood, and socially significant.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The comparison to Sodom and Gomorrah at the judgment is among the most severe in Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 teaching. Sodom and Gomorrah had become the archetypal examples of divine judgment in Jewish tradition (Isa 1:9-10; Jer 23:14; Amos 4:11; 2 Pet 2:6; Jude 7); their sin of refusing hospitality to divine messengers (Gen 19:1-11 — the original context is the refusal of hospitality to angelic visitors) makes the comparison pointedly ironic: towns that refuse hospitality to kingdom messengers share the sin of Sodom.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The "sheep among wolves" (<em>probata en mesō̧ lykōn</em>) metaphor realistically describes the social vulnerability of itinerant missionaries in hostile territory. The paired instructions — wise as serpents (<em>phronimoi hōs hoi opheis</em>), innocent as doves (<em>akeraioi hōs hai peristerai</em>) — draw on Wisdom tradition: the serpent\xe2\x80\x99s wisdom was proverbial (Gen 3:1; Prov 30:24) in a positive sense as discernment; the dove\xe2\x80\x99s harmlessness was a symbol of simplicity and peace. The pairing demands both social intelligence and moral integrity in equal measure.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The warning about councils (<em>synedria</em>) and synagogue floggings (<em>mastigōsousin en tais synagōgais autōn</em>) anticipates real institutional responses to the Christian mission. Synagogue discipline included a flogging of up to forty lashes minus one (based on Deut 25:3, applied as a maximum of 39 to avoid accidental violation of the law) for serious offenses — Paul received this punishment five times (2 Cor 11:24). The councils (<em>synedria</em>) were local judicial bodies in Jewish towns with authority over community discipline matters.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Being dragged before governors and kings (<em>hēgemonas de kai basileis achthēsesthe heneken emou</em>) anticipates the Roman judicial proceedings that would be a feature of early Christian mission. Governors (<em>hēgemones</em>) were Roman provincial administrators; kings (<em>basileis</em>) might refer to client rulers like Herod Agrippa (Acts 12:1-3) or to foreign rulers encountered in mission expansion. The mission context of testimony (<em>eis martyrion autois kai tois ethnesin</em>) frames judicial proceedings as missionary opportunities.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The instruction not to worry about what to say when arrested (<em>mē merimnēsēte pōs ē ti lalēsēte</em>) addresses the social anxiety of appearing before powerful officials without prepared legal defense. Wealthy defendants could afford skilled advocates (<em>rhētores</em>) to present their case; poor defendants spoke for themselves. Jesus promises the Spirit\xe2\x80\x99s assistance in that moment — not as a substitute for thoughtful preparation in general but as specific provision in the crisis of impromptu testimony before authorities.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"For it is not you who speaks but the Spirit of your Father speaking through you" — the theology of prophetic utterance as divine speech rather than merely human articulation has deep roots in Jewish prophetic tradition. Moses claimed inability to speak (Exod 4:10-12) and was promised divine provision; the writing prophets consistently framed their words as divine rather than personal speech. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 impromptu testimony before authorities is placed in this prophetic tradition.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The family-betrayal warnings — brother handing over brother, father handing over child, children rising against parents — reflect the social disruption that covenant-dividing decisions create. Ancient Mediterranean family honor was a collective possession; a family member\xe2\x80\x99s allegiance to a group that brought shame or legal trouble to the whole family created intolerable pressure. The economic and social unit of the family depended on solidarity; Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 mission would fracture exactly this solidarity where it conflicted with kingdom loyalty.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"The one who endures to the end will be saved" (<em>ho de hypomeinas eis telos sōthēsetai</em>) — the temporal framework "until the end" could refer to the end of persecution, the end of one\xe2\x80\x99s life, or the eschatological end. The term <em>hypomenō</em> (endurance, steadfastness under pressure) was a Stoic virtue term that the NT consistently co-opts for covenantal faithfulness: not passive waiting but active, costly perseverance. The universality of the hating ("hated by all on account of my name") makes the endurance-call realistic about the scope of opposition.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The instruction to flee from one city to another when persecuted (<em>pheugete eis tēn allēn</em>) is pragmatic missionary counsel rather than cowardice: the mission field is wide, persecution in one location does not end the mandate, and the preservation of the messenger serves the mission. "Until the Son of Man comes" has generated extensive eschatological debate; in the most immediate reading, it may refer to the coming of the kingdom in judgment on Israel (AD 70), within the lifetime of the disciples.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The student-teacher relationship proverb (<em>ouk estin mathētēs hyper ton didaskalon</em>) and the slave-master analogy draw on well-established social hierarchies in both Jewish and Greco-Roman culture. Disciples expected to share their teacher\xe2\x80\x99s social standing; if the teacher was slandered and opposed, the disciple should expect the same. The application — if they called the master of the house Beelzebul, they will call his household the same — grounds the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 expectation of rejection in Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 own experience.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The name "Beelzebul" (<em>Beelzeboul</em>) is a variation of the name of the Philistine god Baal-Zebub ("lord of flies," 2 Kgs 1:2-3), reinterpreted in Jewish tradition as a demonic title ("lord of the high place" or "lord of the dung"). By the first century it functioned as a name for Satan or the chief demon. The comparison — if Jesus is called Beelzebul, his household (disciples) will be similarly labeled — prepares the disciples for the social consequences of association with a teacher accused of demonic power.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The instruction not to fear them (<em>mē oun phobeisthe autous</em>) begins a section of three paired fear-commands (vv. 26, 28, 31). Each addresses a different object of potential fear: social exposure (v.26), physical death (v.28), and bird-like vulnerability (v.31). The counter to social-exposure fear is the assurance that what is hidden will be revealed — the gospel\xe2\x80\x99s proclamation will eventually overcome the suppression of opponents.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The instruction to proclaim publicly (<em>eipate en tō̄ phōti... kēryxate epi tōn dōmatōn</em>) what was received privately — from ear to public rooftop announcement — reflects the ancient practice of proclamation from housetops. Flat-roofed Palestinian houses were used as elevated platforms for public announcements; town criers and heralds made proclamations from elevated positions so as to be heard throughout a community. The private teaching of disciples is to be amplified into public proclamation.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The distinction between fearing those who can kill the body but not the soul (<em>tēn de psychēn mē dynamenōn apokteinai</em>) and fearing God who can destroy both body and soul in Gehenna (<em>geenna</em>) draws on the theology of martyrdom developing in Second Temple Judaism. The Maccabean martyrs expressed willingness to suffer physical death rather than violate Torah (2 Macc 7:14; 4 Macc 9:8-9), arguing that bodily death was less significant than the loss of the resurrection life. Gehenna (Valley of Hinnom) was the garbage and corpse-burning valley south of Jerusalem, functioning as the image of total destruction.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The sparrow market rate — two sparrows for one assarion (<em>assarion</em> = 1/16 of a denarius, approximately one hour of unskilled labor\xe2\x80\x99s wage) — establishes the smallness and economic insignificance of sparrows. Birds were sold in temple precincts and market areas for sacrifice (doves and pigeons) or food; sparrows at the lowest price point were the cheapest food available to the subsistence poor. The argument from lesser to greater: if God\xe2\x80\x99s providential care extends to the cheapest birds in the market, how much more to human beings.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The numbered hairs of the head (<em>hai triches tēs kephalēs pãsai ērithmēmenai eisin</em>) represents an image of impossibly detailed divine knowledge — the kind of inventory no human being could maintain or use. The average adult human head has 80,000-100,000 hairs; the number and specific attention implied is deliberate hyperbole for exhaustive care. The cultural resonance was with God\xe2\x80\x99s omniscient knowledge celebrated in Ps 139:1-4 and the Wisdom tradition.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"You are worth more than many sparrows" (<em>pollōn strouthiōn diapherete hymeis</em>) — the comparative value argument employs the <em>qal wahomer</em> (lesser to greater) logic: the cheap sparrow\xe2\x80\x99s care implies the greater, not lesser, care for human beings. The encouragement against fear is grounded not in sentiment but in a theological argument about comparative worth and divine attention.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The public confession/denial structure (<em>homologein en emprosthen tōn anthrōpōn / arnēsasthai</em>) reflects the social reality that discipleship would require public identification with Jesus in contexts where that identification carried social risk. In honor-shame culture, public acknowledgment or denial of association was a weighty social act with consequences for both parties. Jesus frames the eschatological judgment as a mirror of present public confession: how one aligns publicly with Jesus determines how Jesus aligns publicly with the disciple before the Father.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The denial parallel — "whoever denies me before men, I will deny before my Father in heaven" — would be powerfully concrete for the disciples after Peter\xe2\x80\x99s triple denial (26:69-75). The judicial language of public acknowledgment and denial was court vocabulary: a patron\xe2\x80\x99s public acknowledgment of a client determined the client\xe2\x80\x99s social standing and legal protection. Jesus positions himself as the eschatological patron whose acknowledgment or denial before God determines ultimate standing.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The "not peace but a sword" declaration (<em>ouk ēlthon balein eirēnēn alla machairan</em>) is a calculated paradox that has been misread as advocating violence. The sword here is not a military weapon but a social divider — the mission creates community fracture along the fault lines of response to Jesus. The peace of the kingdom is ultimate peace; the sword is the inevitable social conflict produced by divided responses to the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s arrival. The OT background is Mic 7:6, which described family division as a sign of covenantal crisis.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The family-division saying — father against son, daughter against mother, daughter-in-law against mother-in-law — explicitly quotes Mic 7:6 and places the mission\xe2\x80\x99s social consequences within a prophetic framework. The Micah passage described the breakdown of trust in family relationships as a symptom of societal covenantal failure. Jesus applies it to the divisions created by responses to his person, making the mission itself the catalyst for this prophetically anticipated social disruption.</p>',
    "36": '<p>The household enemies (<em>hoi echthroi tou anthrōpou hoi oikeioi autou</em> = the enemies of a man are the members of his household) is a direct quotation of Mic 7:6b. In a society where the household was the primary unit of economic survival, security, and social identity, household enmity was the most devastating possible social experience. Jesus is warning that the mission will create this level of disruption — preparing disciples for the most painful form of social opposition they could face.</p>',
    "37": '<p>The love-hierarchy saying — "whoever loves father or mother more than me" (<em>ho philōn patera ē mētera hyper eme</em>) — employs the comparative love-structure of covenant loyalty. Deut 6:5 required whole-heart love for God above all else; the prophets consistently invoked this as the standard for measuring covenant faithfulness. Jesus places himself in the position of the covenant Lord whose claim on loyalty supersedes the strongest natural human bonds. The parallel in Luke 14:26 uses "hate" — a Semitic idiom for preference — which Matthew renders as "love more."</p>',
    "38": '<p>Taking up one\xe2\x80\x99s cross (<em>lambánei ton stauron autou</em>) would have had visceral meaning for first-century Galileans: crucifixion was a publicly visible form of Roman execution and social control. Criminals and revolutionaries were forced to carry the crossbeam (<em>patibulum</em>) to the execution site, a public march of shame and condemnation. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 use of this image before his own crucifixion turns the symbol of Roman power and shame into the description of voluntary covenant discipleship.</p>',
    "39": '<p>The life-losing/finding paradox (<em>ho heurōn tēn psychēn autou apolesei autēn... ho de apolesas tēn psychēn autou heneken emou heurēsei autēn</em>) operates on the distinction between biological/social life (<em>psychē</em> as the self that can be managed and preserved) and eschatological life (what is found through losing). The social context is clear: those who manage their lives carefully to avoid the cost of discipleship lose what matters; those who sacrifice social security for Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 sake find life in its fullest sense.</p>',
    "40": '<p>The reception chain — receiving the disciples receives Jesus, receiving Jesus receives the one who sent him — employs the ancient principle of the authorized representative (<em>shaliach</em> in Jewish law: the agent is as the one who sent him). This gave the mission\xe2\x80\x99s reception enormous theological weight: hospitality to a kingdom messenger was hospitality to Jesus and thereby to the Father. The chain of representation extended divine presence into the mundane act of receiving a traveling teacher.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The reward categories — receiving a prophet "in the name of a prophet" (<em>eis onoma prophētou</em>), receiving a righteous man "in the name of a righteous man" — reflect Second Temple Jewish categories of recognized holy persons. Prophets and righteous men were distinct social types in the Jewish community; each carried specific honor and specific associated reward for their patrons. Receiving them "in their name" means honoring them as what they are — the reception is appropriate to the person\xe2\x80\x99s identity and role.</p>',
    "42": '<p>The cup of cold water (<em>potērion psychrou</em>) for a disciple is the minimum act of hospitality — even this receives a reward. Cold water in the Palestinian climate required access to a spring or cistern; it was more valuable than warm water and was a genuine gesture of care. The "little ones" (<em>tōn mikroōn toutōn</em>) echoes the community ethics of ch. 18 where the "least" are the full bearers of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 presence. The reward principle reaches down to the most minimal act of recognition and care.</p>'
  }
}

comm = load_comm('mkt-context', 'matthew')
